## 5 Number Summary

It describes a dataset using exactly **5 values:**

| # | Name | What it means |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | **Minimum** | Smallest value |
| 2 | **Q1** (25th percentile) | 25% of data is below this |
| 3 | **Median** (Q2) | Middle value, 50% below |
| 4 | **Q3** (75th percentile) | 75% of data is below this |
| 5 | **Maximum** | Largest value |

### Quick Example
```python
data = [2, 5, 7, 8, 10, 12, 15, 18, 20, 25]

Min    = 2
Q1     = 7
Median = 11
Q3     = 18
Max    = 25
```

---

## Box Plot — Visual of the 5 Number Summary

```
    Min   Q1     Median  Q3     Max
     |     |        |     |      |
     ●─────[════════|═════]──────●
               IQR (box)
```

- The **box** spans Q1 → Q3 (called IQR = Q3 - Q1)
- The **line inside box** = Median
- The **whiskers** extend to Min and Max
- **Dots beyond whiskers** = Outliers

---

## Python Code

```python
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

data = [2, 5, 7, 8, 10, 12, 15, 18, 20, 25]

# 5 Number Summary
print("Min    :", np.min(data))
print("Q1     :", np.percentile(data, 25))
print("Median :", np.median(data))
print("Q3     :", np.percentile(data, 75))
print("Max    :", np.max(data))

# Box Plot
plt.boxplot(data)
plt.title("Box Plot")
plt.show()
```

---

## How Outliers are Detected

```
Lower fence = Q1 - 1.5 × IQR
Upper fence = Q3 + 1.5 × IQR

Anything outside these fences = Outlier ⚠️
```

So if IQR = 18 - 7 = **11**:
- Lower fence = 7 - 16.5 = **-9.5**
- Upper fence = 18 + 16.5 = **34.5**
- Nothing in our data exceeds these → **no outliers** ✅

---

## Why It Matters in ML
- Quickly spot **skewness** in data
- Identify **outliers** before training
- Compare **feature distributions** side by side using multiple box plots


## Skewness

Skewness tells you **which side the tail of your data is stretched toward.**

---

## 3 Types

### 1. Normal Distribution (Zero Skew)
```
        ▲
        │    ●
        │   ●●●
        │  ●●●●●
        │ ●●●●●●●
        └──────────→
    Mean = Median = Mode
```
Perfectly symmetric. No skew.

---

### 2. Right Skew (Positive Skew)
```
        ▲
        │●
        │●●
        │●●●
        │●●●●●●●●●●........
        └──────────────────→
    Mode < Median < Mean
```
Tail stretches to the **right.** Mean gets pulled by high values.

**Real example:** Income data — most people earn less, few earn crores → pulls mean right.

---

### 3. Left Skew (Negative Skew)
```
        ▲
                          ●│
                        ●●●│
                      ●●●●●│
        ..........●●●●●●●●●│
        └──────────────────→
    Mean < Median < Mode
```

Tail stretches to the **left.**

**Real example:** Age at retirement — most retire around 60, very few retire very early.

---

## Python Code
```python
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

data = [10, 12, 13, 13, 14, 15, 16, 50, 80, 100]

print("Skewness:", pd.Series(data).skew())
# Positive value = Right skew
# Negative value = Left skew
# Near 0         = Symmetric

plt.hist(data, bins=10)
plt.title("Histogram — check the tail!")
plt.show()
```

---

## Simple Rule to Remember

| Skewness Value | Meaning |
|---|---|
| Near **0** | Symmetric |
| **Positive** (+ve) | Right tail → right skew |
| **Negative** (-ve) | Left tail → left skew |

---

## Why It Matters in ML
- Many algorithms (Linear Regression, etc.) **assume normal distribution**
- High skewness → apply **log transform** or **sqrt transform** to fix it

```python
import numpy as np
df['column'] = np.log1p(df['column'])  # fixes right skew
```

## Outlier

An outlier is a **data point that is very different from the rest of the data** — too high or too low.

---

## Simple Example

```
data = [10, 12, 11, 13, 12, 11, 200]
                                 ↑
                            OUTLIER! 😱
```
Everyone scored around 10-13, but one value is 200 — clearly doesn't belong.

---

## Visual in Box Plot

```
                         Outlier
                            ●
    |                       
    ●──────[══════|═════]──●
    │                      │
   Min                    Max
   (whisker)           (whisker)

Anything beyond whiskers = Outlier
```

---

## How to Detect Outliers

### Method 1 — IQR Method (Most Common)
```python
Q1  = df['col'].quantile(0.25)
Q3  = df['col'].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1

lower = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
upper = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

# Find outliers
outliers = df[(df['col'] < lower) | (df['col'] > upper)]
```

### Method 2 — Z-Score Method
```python
from scipy import stats
import numpy as np

z_scores = np.abs(stats.zscore(df['col']))

# Z-score > 3 = outlier
outliers = df[z_scores > 3]
```

---

## How to Handle Outliers

| Strategy | When to Use |
|---|---|
| **Remove** them | When they're data entry errors |
| **Cap** them (Winsorization) | Keep but limit extreme values |
| **Log transform** | Compress large values |
| **Keep** them | When they're genuine (e.g. fraud detection) |

```python
# Capping example
df['col'] = df['col'].clip(lower=lower, upper=upper)
```

---

## Why It Matters in ML

- **Linear Regression** → outliers drag the line badly
- **Mean** → heavily affected by outliers
- **Median** → not affected ✅ (use this when outliers exist)

```
data  = [10, 11, 12, 13, 200]

Mean   = 49.2  ← pulled by 200 😬
Median = 12    ← not affected ✅
```

---

## Real World Examples
- **Salary data** — CEO salary vs employees
- **House prices** — one mansion in a normal neighborhood
- **Fraud detection** — unusual transaction amount


## Side by Side Box Plots — Compare Feature Distributions

---

## Full Code

```python
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

# ── Create Sample Dataset ───────────────────────────────────────
np.random.seed(42)

df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Age':    np.random.normal(35, 10, 200),      # normal
    'Salary': np.random.exponential(50000, 200),  # right skewed
    'Score':  np.random.uniform(0, 100, 200),     # uniform
    'Height': np.random.normal(165, 15, 200),     # normal
})

# ── Method 1: Simple Side by Side ──────────────────────────────
df.boxplot(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.title("All Features Side by Side")
plt.show()
```

---

## Method 2 — Styled with Subplots (Better)

```python
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 4, figsize=(14, 6))

features = ['Age', 'Salary', 'Score', 'Height']
colors   = ['skyblue', 'salmon', 'lightgreen', 'plum']

for i, (feature, color) in enumerate(zip(features, colors)):
    axes[i].boxplot(
        df[feature],
        patch_artist=True,                        # fills box with color
        boxprops=dict(facecolor=color),
        medianprops=dict(color='black', linewidth=2)
    )
    axes[i].set_title(feature)
    axes[i].set_xlabel("")

plt.suptitle("Feature Distributions Comparison", fontsize=14)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
```

---

## Method 3 — Seaborn (Cleanest)

```python
import seaborn as sns

# Melt dataframe to long format (seaborn needs this)
df_melted = df.melt(var_name='Feature', value_name='Value')

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.boxplot(
    data=df_melted,
    x='Feature',
    y='Value',
    palette='Set2'
)
plt.title("Feature Distributions — Seaborn")
plt.show()
```

---

## What to Look for in Each Box

```
Feature A          Feature B          Feature C
                                          ●  ← outlier
   [═══|══]        [══|══════]       [═══|═]
   Symmetric       Right Skewed       Outliers
   ✅ Good          ⚠️ Log transform    ⚠️ Handle outliers
```

---

## Reading the Comparison

| What You See | What It Means |
|---|---|
| Box is **centered** | Symmetric, normally distributed |
| Box shifted **upward** | Right skew |
| Box shifted **downward** | Left skew |
| **Long whisker** one side | Skewed that direction |
| **Dots** outside whiskers | Outliers |
| **Tall box** | High variance / spread |
| **Short box** | Low variance, consistent data |

